<TITLE> Explosion in Tajik capital kills at least one </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 DUSHANBE, Nov 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - An explosion rocked the centre of the Tajik capital Dushanbe on Wednesday, killing at least one person outside a building where the country's prime minister had been due to make a speech, witnesses said. A Reuters witness at the scene saw at least one body lying on the pavement outside a conference hall located 300 metres (yards) from the presidential palace. It was not immediately clear what caused the blast in Dushanbe, a city of about one million people in the mostly Muslim former Soviet country. Prime Minister Akil Akilov had been due to attend a conference at the Soviet-built hall later in the day. Police and rescue workers have cordoned off the area but were not commenting. Tajikistan, an impoverished nation bordering Afghanistan, is still recovering from a bloody civil war in the 1990s which pitted Moscow-backed secular forces against an alliance of Islamists and opposition-minded libera
